@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction"

@{u}Introduction@{uu}

sFilter is a program for batch (script based) image manipulation.
It`s main usage is to process a sequence of images based on an AREXX script.
It can be used (and this is its intended usage) as a post-processing filter
for a rendering program (e.g. Cinema4D).

@{u}Some features:@{uu}

  o Supports multiple buffers for layering
  o Supports alpha channel operation
  o Filters include basic color changes (saturation, hue, brightness),
    alpha channel operation, convolution, and drawing functions (lines,
    circles, frame, and text)
  o plugin support: plugin functionality is build into shared libraries.
    You can write your own plugins, sample code is included.
  o Scripts are written in AREXX, thus giving you the whole flexibility of
    this language
  o Supports Cinema4D Objectmap files. Create an alpha channel from object map
    to limit operations to object


@endnode
@node Requirements "What you need for sFilter"

@{u}Requirements@{uu}

Currently, sFilter requires the following:

  o Picture datatype V43, and thus, OS 3.x.
    *Should* also work with the Picasso96 datatype.
  o CyberGraphX is not needed for normal filter operation, only
    for interactive work (see the @{"Visual" link visual} command)
  o Some memory :). Depending on how large your frames are, some more :)
    A frame in memory uses width by height by 3 bytes, an alpha channel
    only width by height.
  o AREXX. As AREXX is part of the OS, this should be no problem.
    An assign rexxc: should be set to the directory where rx resides.
    This is needed as Cinema doesn`t set a proper shell environment (no path).
  o For FPU versions, a 020 is the minimum. Supported systems are 68000 (no fpu),
    68020, 68040, 68060 (all including FPU).


@endnode
@node INSTALLATION "Installation"

@{u}Installation@{uu}

Installation is easy. Just double click on the install icon and follow the
on-screen instructions.

@endnode

@node Options "Usage"

@{u}Usage@{uu}

sfilter can only be used from shell or shell-like environment, e.g. it
can be started from Cinema4D. The command template is as follows:

        FILE/A,SCRIPT/K,SHOWINFO/S,FRAME/K/N

@{b}FILE@{ub} is the name of the image file to be operated on. The file is loaded via the
    datatypes system, so every type it supports can be loaded. Saving is done in
    JPEG or PPM P6.
@{b}SCRIPT@{ub} is the name of an AREXX script to be executed with this frame.
@{b}SHOWINFO@{ub} is a switch that, when specified on the command line, will give some
    information: The name of the AREXX port, the frame number, and the name of
    the current file. Only useful for debugging...
@{b}FRAME@{ub} overrides the frame number. Normally, the frame number is derived from the
    filename extension (@{i}file@{ui}.@{i}####@{ui}). This is the way Cinema4D writes its output.
    Other formats will be supported in future versions.


Some examples:

    sFilter frame.0010                      Work on file frame.0010. Nothing
                                            is done, though, as no script is
                                            given. SFilter is listening for
                                            commands on it`s AREXX port.

    sFilter frame.0010 script test.sflt     Work on file frame.0010. Script
                                            test.sflt is executed via the rx
                                            command

    sfilter $bild script rexx:test.sflt     Invoke sfilter from Cinema4D. Note
                                            that $bild is for the german version.
                                            My guess is $picture for the english
                                            Version, but you`d better have a look
                                            at the manual :)

    sfilter pic frame 10                    Override the frame number.

@endnode
@node OPERATION "Operation"

@{u}Operation@{uu}

As mentioned before, sFilter is used with an AREXX script. This script is invoked
with the rexxc:rx command (Note that the assign must be set. See @{"Requirements" link Requirements}
for details why). The name of the AREXX port is given to the script as the first
parameter. This can be read (in AREXX) by the following code fragment:

    /* Get the AREXX port name */

    parse arg port

    address VALUE port

    /* Do something */

This reads the port name and sets it. From here on, commands can be issued to sFilter.


@{u}Basic principles@{uu}

@{b}Buffers@{ub}
sFilter operates on named buffers. A buffer is simply a chunk of memory representing
a picture frame. Buffers can be created, deleted, image data can be loaded into them
and single buffers can be converted into alpha channels. Although buffers can be
created at any size, the default behavior is to create buffers at the same size
as the primary frame. The primary frame, once loaded, is always accessible under
the name 'default'.

@{b}Colors@{ub}
Colors are specified as RGB triplets. All components are in the range from
0 to 255.

@{b}Numbers@{ub}
Fractional numbers are defined scaled to 255. To make this clearer, consider the
following example:
Changing saturation to 0 means that no color will be left in the image (grayscale).
A saturation of 255 is equivalent to 1.0 (no color change). A value of 511 means
saturation is doubled.

@{b}Coordinates@{ub}
The coordinate system has X growing from left to right, and Y growing from top to
bottom.

@{b}Alpha channel@{ub}
Alpha channeling is done via linear interpolation. Alpha data is in the range
from 0 to 255, with 255 being full transparency.

@{b}AREXX@{ub}
sFilter uses dos/ReadArgs for parsing. This function does not recognize floating
point numbers. Therefore, you must @{b}TRUNC()@{ub} all floating point numbers.

@endnode
@node COMMANDS "Commands"

@{u}Commands@{uu}

There are two major groups of commands: internal and external (plugin commands).
Internal command include management functions and text functions, while external
functions provide different possibilities. The functions are:

@{b}Control functions:@{ub}
    @{"     Quit     " link QUIT} - Quit sfilter.
    @{"   UsePlugin  " link USEPLUGIN} - Prepare an external plugin for use.
    @{"    Visual    " link VISUAL} - Switch visual mode.
    @{"    Window    " link WINDOW} - Set a window on the current frame.
    @{"  FrameInfo   " link FRAMEINFO} - Get information on frame.

@{b}Buffer management functions:@{ub}
    @{"   LoadFrame  " link LOADFRAME} - Load the frame indicated on command line.
    @{"   SaveFrame  " link SAVEFRAME} - Save the frame.
    @{" CreateBuffer " link CREATEBUFFER} - Create a new buffer.
    @{" DeleteBuffer " link DELETEBUFFER} - Delete the named buffer.
    @{"   UseBuffer  " link USEBUFFER} - Use the named buffer for all subsequent operation.
    @{"   UseSecond  " link USESECOND} - Use the named buffer as secondary buffer.
    @{"  LoadBuffer  " link LOADBUFFER} - Load a file and create a new buffer with it.
    @{" ClearBuffer  " link CLEARBUFFER} - Clear a named buffer to a given color.
    @{"  CopyBuffer  " link COPYBUFFER} - Copy one buffer into another.

@{b}Alpha channel management functions:@{ub}
    @{"   MakeAlpha  " link MAKEALPHA} - Create an alpha channel from a given buffer.
    @{"  ClearAlpha  " link CLEARALPHA} - Clear alpha channel to a given value
    @{" InvertAlpha  " link INVERTALPHA} - Invert the alpha channel.

@{b}Text functions:@{ub}
    @{"    GotoXY    " link GOTOXY} - Set current print position (remember BASIC ?).
    @{"     Font     " link FONT} - Open an Amiga font.
    @{"     Pen      " link PEN} - Set a pen to given color.
    @{"    Print     " link PRINT} - Print text.

@{b}Object map functions:@{ub}
    @{"    LoadOM    " link LOADOM} - Load a Cinema4D object map.
    @{"   OMSelect   " link OMSELECT} - "Paint" an object to a named buffer.



The following functions are external and must be '@{b}UsePlugin@{ub}ed'. Note that
when specifying plugin names case @{i}does@{ui} matter.

@{b}Color:@{ub}
    @{"    Balance   " link BALANCE} - Color balancing
    @{"  Brightness  " link BRIGHTNESS} - Change the brightness
    @{"   Contrast   " link CONTRAST} - Change contrast
    @{"  Grayscale   " link GRAYSCALE} - Change buffer to grayscale
    @{"  Saturation  " link SATURATION} - Change color saturation
    @{"     Tint     " link TINT} - Change the overall color

@{b}Effects:@{ub}
    @{"   Convolve   " link CONVOLVE} - Do a matrix convolution
    @{"     Glow     " link GLOW} - Make an OMSelected object glow
    @{" Interpolate  " link INTERPOLATE} - Interpolate one buffer with another
    @{"    Noise     " link NOISE} - Add noise to the frame
    @{"     RGB      " link RGB} - Do a color separation
    @{"    Video     " link VIDEO} - Make the buffer look like a video screen

@{b}Drawing:@{ub}
    @{"     Box      " link BOX} - Draw a filled box
    @{"    Circle    " link CIRCLE} - Draw an unfilled circle
    @{"     Disc     " link DISC} - Draw a filled circle
    @{"    Frame     " link FRAME} - Draw an unfilled frame
    @{"     Line     " link LINE} - Draw a line
    @{"     Plot     " link PLOT} - Draw a dot

@{b}Buffer to buffer operation:@{ub}
    @{"    Boole     " link BOOLE} - Do a boolean operation between two buffers
    @{"     Mix      " link MIX} - Mix two buffers with alpha channeling


@endnode

@node QUIT "Quit"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    QUIT

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    This command simply quits sfilter. @{u}Warning:@{uu} @{i}Nothing will be saved.@{ui} Your data
    is only saved when you issue the @{"SaveFrame" link SAVEFRAME} command.

@endnode

@node USEPLUGIN "UsePlugin"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin   NAME/M,ALL/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Initialize a plugin library for use in the current script. Plugins are implemented
    as shared libraries. The UsePlugin command asks the named plugin for the command it
    provides.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME    One or more names of plugins. The name of a plugin is the name of the library
            without the .library suffix. Note that case matters, e.g. grayscale != GRAYSCALE.
            Note that AREXX converts all strings to upper case, unless they are surrounded by
            single quotes (').

    ALL     Instead of giving names, you can use the ALL keyword. The plugin directory
            is being scanned and all plugins are activated. Note, though, that no matter how
            many plugins are activated, only one will be in memory at any time. In normal
            cases, you can use the ALL switch.


@endnode

@node VISUAL "Visual"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    Visual  ON/S,OFF/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Switch "visual" mode. In visual mode, a window is opened and all operations
    are shown in it. A frame must be loaded (via the @{"LoadFrame" link LOADFRAME} command).
    @{u}Note:@{uu} @{i}Visual mode is not available if you don`t have CyberGraphX! @{ui} Note,
    though, that even if you have CyberGraphX, visual mode is only available if the window
    actually @{i}opens@{ui} on a CyberGraphX screen

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    ON      Switch visual mode on.

    OFF     Switch visual mode off (surprise!)


@endnode

@node WINDOW "Window"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    Window  X/N,Y/N,W/N,H/N,DEFAULT/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Set a window on the current buffer. All subsequent operation only affect the region
    defined by the window.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    X,Y         Define the upper right corner of the window

    W,H         Width and height of the window

    DEFAULT     Set window to full buffer size. Note that changing buffers
                also resets the window

    @{u}Note:@{uu} Either DEFAULT, or dimensions @{i}must@{ui} be given.


@endnode
@node FRAMEINFO "FrameInfo"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    FrameInfo   NUMBER/S,WIDTH/S,HEIGHT/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Returns information on current (loaded) frame. The result is returned
    via the normal AREXX @{b}OPTIONS RESULTS@{ub} command.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}

        OPTIONS RESULTS
        FrameInfo NUMBER
        frame = result

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NUMBER      Return the number of the current frame

    WIDTH       Return width

    HEIGHT      Return height


@endnode
@node LOADFRAME "LoadFrame"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    LoadFrame

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Load the frame indicated by command line argument FILE to memory. Note that this
    command must be executed before any other buffer can be created. A buffer named
    @{b}default@{ub} is created.


@endnode

@node SAVEFRAME "SaveFrame"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    SaveFrame   PPM/S,STDOUT/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Save the buffer named @{b}default@{ub} to a JPEG or PPM file. The name is
    indicated by the command line argument FILE (i.e. the original file is
    overwritten). If no argument is given, a JPEG file will be written, with
    a quality setting of 95 %.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    PPM         Write a PPM P6 file instead of JPEG. This option is included
                to support a non-lossy format. At the present time, I am working
                on a IFF  writer. Unfortunately, there is not much information
                available on 24 bit IFFs, let alone compressed ones (same goes for
                datatypes). If you want to directly write an IFF file, use the
                STDOUT keyword (see below) and pipe it to something like ppmtoilbm.

    STDOUT      Can only be used with PPM. The PPM file is written to stdout.
                The output can be piped to an external program, e.g. a netpbm
                program, whirlgif, or mpegencode.

@endnode

@node CREATEBUFFER "CreateBuffer"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    CreateBuffer    NAME/A,X/N,Y/N,DEFAULT/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Create a new buffer. The buffer is not clear, so it`s contents is complete
    garbage.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        Every buffer is identified by a unique name. This parameter specifies
                it.

    X,Y         Dimensions of the buffer. These @{i}can@{ui} be different from the
                "default" dimensions. Currently, this is useless because no operations
                between different sized buffers can be made. It is implemented for
                future versions.

    DEFAULT     Set the dimensions of the buffer to the dimensions of the @{b}default@{ub}
                buffer.

@endnode

@node DELETEBUFFER "DeleteBuffer"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    DeleteBuffer    NAME/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Delete the named buffer. All memory is freed and it`s contents is lost.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        Name of the buffer to be deleted


@endnode

@node USEBUFFER "UseBuffer"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    UseBuffer   NAME/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Set the named buffer to be the current buffer. All subsequent operation
    is done on this buffer.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        Name of the buffer to be used

@endnode

@node USESECOND "UseSecond"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    UseSecond   NAME/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Set the named buffer to be the current secondary buffer. Some operations do
    require this (e.g. convolution, mixing).


@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        Name of the buffer to be used as secondary

@endnode

@node LOADBUFFER "LoadBuffer"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    LoadBuffer  NAME/A,FILE/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Create a new buffer and load an image file into it. The file is loaded via
    datatypes.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        The name of the new buffer

    FILE        The name of the file

@endnode

@node CLEARBUFFER "ClearBuffer"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    ClearBuffer     NAME/A,R/N,G/N,B/N

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Clear a named buffer to a selected color (defined in RGB)

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        Name of the buffer

    R/G/B       The color to clear the buffer with

@endnode

@node COPYBUFFER "CopyBuffer"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    CopyBuffer  FROM/A,TO/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Copy buffer @{b}from@{ub} to buffer @{b}to@{ub}.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    FROM        Name of the source buffer

    TO          Name of the target buffer

@endnode

@node MAKEALPHA "MakeAlpha"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    MakeAlpha   NAME,THRESHOLD=T/N,VALUE/N

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Convert named buffer to alpha channel. The color data from the buffer is converted
    to the corresponding gray levels and put into the alpha channel.
    If THRESHOLD/VALUE is given, the current foreground pen (see @{"Pen" link PEN}) is taken as a
    transparent color, and all colors with euclidian distance smaller than
    THRESHOLD are set to zero in the alpha channel, while all others are set to VALUE.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        Name of the buffer to be converted

    THRESHOLD   Maximum distance from foreground pen

    VALUE       Value to set for opaque pixels

@endnode

@node CLEARALPHA "ClearAlpha"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    ClearAlpha  LEVEL/N

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Clear alpha channel to LEVEL

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    LEVEL       Value to clear the alpha channel with.

@endnode

@node INVERTALPHA "InvertAlpha"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    InvertAlpha

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Inverts the alpha channel by negating all bytes (i.e. alpha = ~alpha).

@endnode

@node GOTOXY "GotoXY"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    GotoXY      X=COLUMN/N/A,Y=LINE/N/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Set the current print position to x,y. Note that these coordinates are the
    top left corner of the text box, not the baseline like in graphics.library
    Text function.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    X           The x coordinate (or column) for printing. This is given in
                @{i}pixel@{ui} coordinates.

    Y           The y coordinate (or line) for printing. This is also given
                in pixel coordinates

@endnode

@node FONT "Font"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    Font        NAME/A,SIZE/N/A

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Load an Amiga font into memory. This can be any font available in your system,
    with the exception of color fonts. Outline fonts are supported.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    NAME        The name of the font. This must be given in full, i.e. @{b}topaz.font@{ub}.

    SIZE        Height of the font in pixels. Fonts are scaled automatically if they are
                not available in that size.


@endnode

@node PEN "Pen"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    Pen     RED=R/N/A,GREEN=G/N/A,BLUE=B/N/A,FOREGROUND=FG/S,BACKGROUND=BG/S,
                HILITE=HL/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Sets the pen specified by FOREGROUND, BACKGROUND or HILITE to the specified
    color. sFilter uses three pens, Foreground, Background, and Hilite. These pens
    are used for different operations, including printing and drawing.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    R,G,B       Specifies red, green and blue components

    FOREGROUND  Set this color to be the foreground (drawing) pen.

    BACKGROUND  Set this color to be the background (eraser) pen.

    HILITE      Set this color to be the hilite pen.

@endnode
@node PRINT "Print"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    Print       TEXT/A,FRAME/N/A,END/N/A,RATE/N/A,BRIGHT/S,FLARE/S,CURSOR/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Print a text to the current buffer. The text is printed according to the frame
    numbers and rate specified.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    TEXT        The text to be printed. If the text contains spaces, it must
                be put into quotes like that:
                @{b}'"Blah fasel"'@{ub}

    FRAME       Starting frame. Starting with this frame, the text is displayed
                with rate RATE.

    END         End frame. After this frame, the text is no longer displayed.

    RATE        The frame rate which is used to output text. If it is 0, the
                whole text is printed at frame FRAME and stays on screen until
                END. If non-zero, every RATE frame, a new letter is printed.
                Example:
                    Print 'Test' 10 100 2
                Starting with frame 10, characters are written every two frames.
                When all is output, the text stays on "screen", until frame 100
                is reached.

    BRIGHT      Normal text is printed in the foreground color. If BRIGHT is set,
                the last letter is printed in the HILITE pen color.

    CURSOR      A "cursor" is printed after the text.

    FLARE       A "flare" effect is overlayed on the last letter.

@endnode

@node LOADOM "LoadOM"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    LoadOM      DEFAULT/S,FILE/K

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Load the object map for this frame, or a user define object map.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    DEFAULT     Load the default map (i.e. @{i}file@{ui}.OM)

    FILE        An alternate file name (full name, including the
                extension).

@endnode

@node OMSELECT "OMSelect"

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    OMSelect    BUFFER/A,OBJECT,SKY/S,GROUND/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    "Paint" the named OBJECT into the buffer BUFFER, i.e. all pixels occupied
    by the named object are set to the foreground pen color.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    BUFFER      Name of the buffer to be used.

    OBJECT      Name of the object

    SKY         Select the sky. No object name must be given

    GROUND      Select the ground. No object name must be given

@endnode

@node BALANCE "Balance"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'balance'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    BALANCE     RED=R/N/A,GREEN=G/N/A,BLUE=B/N/A,ALPHA/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Balance color in current buffer. The red, green and blue component are raised
    (positive value) or lowered (negative value) according to parameters. Values
    are given according to the fractional number rule in @{"Operation" link Operation}.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    RED         Scale value for red.

    GREEN       Same as above, green.

    BLUE        Same as above, blue.

    ALPHA       Use the alpha channel. The values are computed and interpolated between
                original (buffer) value, and new (computed) value, weighted by alpha.
@endnode

@node BRIGHTNESS "Brightness"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin   'brightness'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    BRIGHTNESS  LEVEL/A/N,ALPHA/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Change the brightness of a buffer.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    LEVEL       Level of change. Positive numbers raise brightness, negative numbers
                lower it.

    ALPHA       Use alpha channel for this operation
@endnode

@node CONTRAST "Contrast"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'contrast'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    CONTRAST    AMOUNT/A/N,ALPHA/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Change the contrast of the buffer.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    AMOUNT      Amount of change.

    ALPHA       Use alpha channel
@endnode

@node GRAYSCALE "Grayscale"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'grayscale'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    GRAYSCALE   ALPHA/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Convert a buffer to grayscale.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    ALPHA       Use alpha channel

@endnode

@node SATURATION "Saturation"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'saturation'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    SATURATION  LEVEL/A/N,ALPHA/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Change color saturation for this buffer. A value of -255 removes
    all color, positive values enhance it.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    LEVEL       Amount of change

    ALPHA       Use alpha channel

@endnode

@node TINT "Tint"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'tint'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    TINT    RED=R/N,GREEN=G/N,BLUE=B/N,ALPHA/S,ANTIQUE/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Tint a buffer (i.e. colorize).

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    RED         Color to tint to.
    GREEN
    BLUE

    ALPHA       Use alpha channel.

    ANTIQUE     Use "antique" coloring scheme (yellowish brown).

@endnode

@node CONVOLVE "Convolve"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'convolve'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    CONVOLVE    A/N,B/N,C/N,D/N,E/N,F/N,G/N,H/N,I/N,Q/N

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Convolve the primary buffer and put the result into the secondary
    buffer, without changing the source.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    A B C       Convolution matrix components.
    D E F
    G H I

        Q       Quotient. If none is given, the sum of all matrix
                components will be used.

@endnode

@node GLOW "Glow"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'glow'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    GLOW    X/N/A,Y/N/A,SCALE/N,NOCOPY/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    The glow effect makes an object that was previously "selected" glow.
    Data is read from the primary buffer, and put into the secondary.


@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    X,Y     The size of the glow effect. The effect is implemented as a
            rectangular weighted sum. X and Y give the width and height of
            this rectangle. @{i}Note:@{ui} This effect can be really slow, especially
            with large X and Y values.

    SCALE   Scale factor to "lighten up" the glow.

    NOCOPY  Do not copy pixels from primary buffers (i.e. the secondary buffer will
            only contain the outline of the object).


@endnode

@node INTERPOLATE "Interpolate"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'interpolate'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    INTERPOLATE AMOUNT/N,SECONDARY=SEC/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Interpolate color values from primary buffer to alpha channel, or from
    primary buffer to secondary via alpha channel. This function is @{i}very@{ui} powerful,
    although describing it in full is beyond the scope of this manual. For a
    good description of the effect, see
        @{b}http://www.sgi.com/grafica/interp/index.htm@{ub}

    For examples, look at
        @{i}http://www.informatik.uni-trier.de/CIP/hfrieden/@{ui}
    in the tutorials section (coming soon).

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    AMOUNT      Weight of interpolation. Must be given when no secondary is given.
                Corresponds to a constant secondary buffer.

    SECONDARY   Use the secondary buffer for interpolation. The color information
                in this buffer is converted to its gray value, and interpolation
                is done between buffer data and alpha channel data weighted by
                this grey value on a pixel per pixel basis (boy, this is hard
                to explain!!).

@{u}@{i}Example:@{ui}@{uu}

    I guess an example would be handy here:

    When lowering saturation in an image, the color values of the picture
    are "moved" towards gray. This can be expressed by a linear interpolation
    between a color and its gray level. The amount of this interpolation is
    given by the AMOUNT parameter. Thus, you can simulate a saturation filter
    by converting a frame to an alpha channel (remember that the alpha channel
    is made of the gray values of the frame) and then interpolating by an amount
    equal to the amount of saturation change.

    Another possibility is sharpening: Convolve the buffer with a gaussian
    blur matrix (all ones) to the secondary buffer, convert the latter to alpha
    channel, and interpolate. The mount of interpolation represents the amount
    of sharpening.

    The Grafica Obscura article gives more details on this, and it`s worth
    reading.

@endnode
@node NOISE "Noise"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'noise'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    NOISE   AMOUNT/N/A,ALPHA/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Adds random noise to the picture by changing the brightness of pixels.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    AMOUNT      Maximum noise amplitude.

    ALPHA       Use alpha channel.

@endnode

@node RGB "RGB"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'RGB'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    RGB     R=RED/S,G=GREEN/S,BLUE=B/S

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Do a color "separation". All color components @{i}not@{ui} given in the parameter
    list are set to zero. @{i}Note:@{ui} This function is only useful for things like
    MPEG encoders, so no alpha channel is supported.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    RED         The color components to be left in the buffer.
    GREEN
    BLUE

@endnode

@node VIDEO "Video"

@{b}@{u}"UsePlugin" name:@{uu}@{ub}

    UsePlugin 'video'

@{b}@{u}Command template:@{uu}@{ub}

    VIDEO   AMOUNT/N

@{b}@{u}Function:@{uu}@{ub}

    Make the current buffer look like a video screen. Every other line
    is reduced in brightness.

@{b}@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{ub}

    AMOUNT      Factor by which brightness is reduced.
@endnode

